Using kable() for formatting in labs

When printing rows of a data frame or tibble
need to load the knitr package at the beginning of your file

kable() outputs a markdown version of your data
should only be used to nicely format data you are printing




e.g.

cereal |&gt; 
  mutate(ratio = sugars / potass) |&gt; 
  slice_head(n = 3) |&gt; 
  kable()


NOT

cereal_clean &lt;- cereal |&gt; 
  mutate(ratio = sugars / potass) |&gt; 
  slice_head(n = 3) |&gt; 
  kable()

Problem A - Fizz Buzz
Suppose you have a vector of numbers (e.g., 1:100). For each value, you want to print the following output:

if a number is divisible by 3, print "Fizz",
if the number is divisible by 5, print "Buzz",
if the number is divisible by both 3 and 5, print "FizzBuzz",
if none of these are true then print the number.








Pencil it Out


Brainstorm how you would write R code to solve this problem. Your solution must use a for()-loop.

Dog Sitter

total_wetfood &lt;- 0
total_dryfood &lt;- 0

for(i in 1:nrow(dogs)){
  # Small dogs
  if(dogs$size[i] == "small"){
    # Old dogs
    if(dogs$age[i] &gt; 12){
      total_wetfood &lt;- total_wetfood + 8
    } 
    # Younger dogs
    else{
      total_dryfood &lt;- total_dryfood + 8
    }
  } 
  # Medium dogs
  else if(dogs$size[i] == "medium"){
    # Older dogs
    if(dogs$age[i] &gt; 12){
      total_wetfood &lt;- total_wetfood + 16
    } 
    # Younger dogs
    else{
      total_dryfood &lt;- total_dryfood + 16
      }
  } 
  # Large dogs
  else{
    # Old dogs
    if(dogs$age[i] &gt; 12){
      total_wetfood &lt;- total_wetfood + 32
    } 
    # Younger dogs
    else{
      total_dryfood &lt;- total_dryfood + 32
      }
    }
}





